WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.505 --> 00:00:03.088
(bright music)

2
00:00:07.950 --> 00:00:10.860
<v Host>Dr. Firnhaber is returning</v>

3
00:00:10.860 --> 00:00:12.690
for the final presentation

4
00:00:12.690 --> 00:00:16.440
as we look at cardiovascular medicine.

5
00:00:16.440 --> 00:00:18.720
Jonathon's gonna talk about dysrhythmias.

6
00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:19.830
Take it away, sir.

7
00:00:19.830 --> 00:00:21.330
<v ->All right, let's do this.</v>

8
00:00:21.330 --> 00:00:24.810
So we're doing dysrhythmias, which is also,

9
00:00:24.810 --> 00:00:26.010
I mean, aren't they all fun?

10
00:00:26.010 --> 00:00:28.230
And the cardiac topics to me are just fascinating.

11
00:00:28.230 --> 00:00:29.370
I love the physiology.

12
00:00:29.370 --> 00:00:32.700
All right, so if you know,

13
00:00:32.700 --> 00:00:36.360
I think I put up the cardiac,

14
00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:37.560
the coronary circulation,

15
00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:40.380
basically as you need to know, you know,

16
00:00:40.380 --> 00:00:43.290
where the right and left corona artery are circumflex.

17
00:00:43.290 --> 00:00:44.910
Basically what those all covered,

18
00:00:44.910 --> 00:00:45.960
this is really all you need

19
00:00:45.960 --> 00:00:48.480
to know about the coronary conduction system.

20
00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:49.313
The wiring.

21
00:00:49.313 --> 00:00:52.080
So SA node sits high up in the right atrium.

22
00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:53.330
So when you're looking at an EKG

23
00:00:53.330 --> 00:00:57.150
and you see abnormalities in the initial part of the P wave,

24
00:00:57.150 --> 00:01:00.060
the atria depolarize right to left.

25
00:01:00.060 --> 00:01:03.600
So the P wave is right atrial depolarization followed

26
00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:06.030
by left atrial depolarization.

27
00:01:06.030 --> 00:01:09.330
SA node conduction both hard wire and intrinsic path

28
00:01:09.330 --> 00:01:12.840
and intrinsic pathways go down to AV node

29
00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:15.390
which sits between the atria and ventricles.

30
00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:18.450
Next up is the bundle of His which quickly splits apart

31
00:01:18.450 --> 00:01:21.390
to the right bundle, which is only the right bundle.

32
00:01:21.390 --> 00:01:23.070
The left bundle is fairly short

33
00:01:23.070 --> 00:01:25.860
because it splits apart again into both an anterior

34
00:01:25.860 --> 00:01:27.333
and a posterior fascial.

35
00:01:29.070 --> 00:01:31.590
If you're trying to correlate both the conducting system

36
00:01:31.590 --> 00:01:33.900
and the circulatory system,

37
00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:36.420
typically the the AV node is supplied

38
00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:37.560
by the right coronary artery,

39
00:01:37.560 --> 00:01:39.900
which also supplies the inferior wall.

40
00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:42.870
Therefore, inferior MIs, more often than not,

41
00:01:42.870 --> 00:01:45.150
will cause AV conduction abnormalities

42
00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:47.250
or AV nodal ischemia.

43
00:01:47.250 --> 00:01:48.870
Anterior wall of the heart.

44
00:01:48.870 --> 00:01:52.410
The LAD also supplies the distal conducting system,

45
00:01:52.410 --> 00:01:54.240
the His Purkinje system.

46
00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:56.460
Why that's important is the AV node tends

47
00:01:56.460 --> 00:01:57.810
to recover more readily

48
00:01:57.810 --> 00:01:59.850
than the distal conducting system does.

49
00:01:59.850 --> 00:02:03.180
So anterior MIs with conduction abnormalities tend not

50
00:02:03.180 --> 00:02:05.493
to see recovery of electrical conduction.

51
00:02:07.110 --> 00:02:08.790
All right, so let's go right to a question.

52
00:02:08.790 --> 00:02:10.620
We've got a 52-year-old male

53
00:02:10.620 --> 00:02:13.680
who's got a blood pressure of 154 over 86.

54
00:02:13.680 --> 00:02:15.630
He's an avid tennis player.

55
00:02:15.630 --> 00:02:17.370
Past history is benign.

56
00:02:17.370 --> 00:02:19.380
Given this rhythm strip,

57
00:02:19.380 --> 00:02:21.480
which of the following drugs would be inappropriate

58
00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:24.750
to use in this patient for treatment of his hypertension?

59
00:02:24.750 --> 00:02:27.333
So first take a look at the rhythm strip.

60
00:02:27.333 --> 00:02:29.010
(audience laughing)

61
00:02:29.010 --> 00:02:30.513
It is a funny one, isn't it?

62
00:02:32.214 --> 00:02:36.990
Yeah, so if you're trying to count boxes, 300, 150, 175, 60,

63
00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:39.720
just below 60, it's like a heart rate of maybe 58,

64
00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:40.983
somewhere in there.

65
00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:45.120
All right, so there's the rhythm strip.

66
00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:48.300
Which drugs would be inappropriate?

67
00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:51.030
Either a dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker,

68
00:02:51.030 --> 00:02:53.550
non-dihydrodpyridine calcium channel blocker,

69
00:02:53.550 --> 00:02:56.105
beta blocker, or cyanide.

70
00:02:56.105 --> 00:02:59.105
(audience laughing)

71
00:03:00.930 --> 00:03:02.535
So what concerns me is that...

72
00:03:02.535 --> 00:03:05.580
(audience laughing)

73
00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:07.320
59% of you seem

74
00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:09.994
to think that cyanide is still an okay choice.

75
00:03:09.994 --> 00:03:12.720
(audience laughing)

76
00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:13.553
It's not.

77
00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:17.520
Please don't prescribe cyanide for your patients.

78
00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:19.920
And they're not gonna be this easy on the board exam

79
00:03:19.920 --> 00:03:21.783
so be prepared.

80
00:03:22.650 --> 00:03:26.820
The point is that all the other drugs are fine except

81
00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:27.653
for cyanide.

82
00:03:27.653 --> 00:03:28.830
So what we saw here,

83
00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:31.170
two things of note on this rhythm strip.

84
00:03:31.170 --> 00:03:32.490
One was sinus bradycardia

85
00:03:32.490 --> 00:03:35.430
and the second is that there's a first degree AV block.

86
00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:38.430
And the important point is neither of those findings

87
00:03:38.430 --> 00:03:41.340
by themselves is an absolute contraindication

88
00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:45.240
to a drug that slows heart rate or slows AV conduction.

89
00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:47.430
Meaning if you had a compelling reason,

90
00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:48.263
granted, you know,

91
00:03:48.263 --> 00:03:50.730
you're probably not gonna start a beta blocker first line

92
00:03:50.730 --> 00:03:52.680
for this individual for blood pressure.

93
00:03:52.680 --> 00:03:53.880
He's an avid tennis player.

94
00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:55.320
He's already a bit bradycardic.

95
00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:57.870
But if you had a compelling reason to use a beta blocker,

96
00:03:57.870 --> 00:03:59.280
then you use a beta blocker.

97
00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:00.540
The first degree AV block

98
00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:03.120
and even the slow heart rate

99
00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:06.480
are not absolute contraindications to either a beta blocker

100
00:04:06.480 --> 00:04:10.230
or to a calcium channel blocker that slows AV conduction.

101
00:04:10.230 --> 00:04:12.930
Remember verapamil slows AV conduction slightly more

102
00:04:12.930 --> 00:04:15.810
than does verapamil, the non-dihydropyridine,

103
00:04:15.810 --> 00:04:18.120
so excuse me, the dihydropyridine.

104
00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:20.280
So all the pain drugs technically

105
00:04:20.280 --> 00:04:23.043
shouldn't slow AV conduction significantly.

106
00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:27.210
All right, this one isn't quite as easy.

107
00:04:27.210 --> 00:04:30.870
Question two, just that there's not a cyanide one there.

108
00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:32.100
52-year-old male with COPD

109
00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:34.500
and hypertension has worsening fatigue.

110
00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:36.660
He denies chest pain, shortness of breath.

111
00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:39.660
Exam is notable for a slow, irregular pulse.

112
00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:40.770
Lungs are clear.

113
00:04:40.770 --> 00:04:43.860
Medications include lisinopril, chlorthalidone,

114
00:04:43.860 --> 00:04:46.710
tiotropium inhaled, and aspirin.

115
00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:48.120
Based on his history and this rhythm strip,

116
00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:49.320
what's the diagnosis?

117
00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:50.720
So what are you seeing here?

118
00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:55.230
So we've got options,

119
00:04:55.230 --> 00:05:00.230
A, blocked PAC, Mobitz type one, Mobitz type two,

120
00:05:01.950 --> 00:05:03.993
or third degree AV block.

121
00:05:05.130 --> 00:05:06.380
What were you looking at?

122
00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:14.730
Okay, so the majority going

123
00:05:14.730 --> 00:05:17.010
with a second degree type one, which is correct.

124
00:05:17.010 --> 00:05:19.170
So let's take a look at this.

125
00:05:19.170 --> 00:05:22.110
Second degree type one is fairly common thing.

126
00:05:22.110 --> 00:05:24.840
If you read over Holter monitors for example,

127
00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:28.410
or our organization, we use the Zio monitor,

128
00:05:28.410 --> 00:05:30.660
which is one you can use up to 14 days.

129
00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:33.990
And I read all of our department's monitors

130
00:05:33.990 --> 00:05:37.470
probably one out of 20, somewhere in there,

131
00:05:37.470 --> 00:05:40.200
I'll see someone will have an overnight episode

132
00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:42.180
of a second degree type one block.

133
00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:44.550
They basically drop a beat in there someplace.

134
00:05:44.550 --> 00:05:47.190
So progressive PR interval lengthening,

135
00:05:47.190 --> 00:05:48.480
meaning that the AV node

136
00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:50.880
is becoming progressively more fatigued,

137
00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:53.760
less likely to conduct, to finally have a P wave

138
00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:56.940
that just doesn't get through and you've got a dropped beat.

139
00:05:56.940 --> 00:05:59.550
We do term this as second degree AV block

140
00:05:59.550 --> 00:06:02.640
and this is almost always an AV nodal problem.

141
00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:04.770
It's usually not a significant problem is the thing.

142
00:06:04.770 --> 00:06:08.700
So if you happen to see someone who drops a beat overnight,

143
00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:11.010
they're a younger, typically more athletic

144
00:06:11.010 --> 00:06:13.230
or more physically fit individual,

145
00:06:13.230 --> 00:06:16.650
high overnight vagal tone may see enough vagal tone

146
00:06:16.650 --> 00:06:18.330
that the AV conduction slows enough

147
00:06:18.330 --> 00:06:19.920
that they periodically drop a beat.

148
00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:21.000
Doesn't mean much.

149
00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.820
They rouse, they wake up, vagal tone decreases,

150
00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:25.800
conduction through the AV node improves,

151
00:06:25.800 --> 00:06:27.480
and conduction normalizes.

152
00:06:27.480 --> 00:06:28.803
So not a big issue.

153
00:06:29.970 --> 00:06:31.890
If you do see this in the acute setting,

154
00:06:31.890 --> 00:06:33.600
again, the right coronary artery,

155
00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:35.820
which supplies the inferior wall of the heart,

156
00:06:35.820 --> 00:06:37.510
typically supplies the AV node.

157
00:06:37.510 --> 00:06:40.680
So in the setting of inferior ischemia

158
00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:44.700
or an inferior infarct, you may also see AV nodal ischemia

159
00:06:44.700 --> 00:06:47.850
and may see this particular rhythm.

160
00:06:47.850 --> 00:06:50.370
Important thing, take care of the underlying ischemia.

161
00:06:50.370 --> 00:06:52.710
This is not one to, you know, call cardiologists.

162
00:06:52.710 --> 00:06:54.960
They'll simply snicker at you and say, "You know what?

163
00:06:54.960 --> 00:06:56.760
Take care of the ischemia.

164
00:06:56.760 --> 00:06:59.277
Don't worry about the second degree type one."

165
00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:04.410
So this is second degree type two AV block.

166
00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:06.390
And so the difference here,

167
00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:08.100
you'll notice that one of the hallmarks

168
00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:11.100
of a second degree AV block is

169
00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:12.420
that basically you've got a gap.

170
00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:14.070
Everything was going fine.

171
00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:17.460
You were expecting a beat right here and it didn't happen.

172
00:07:17.460 --> 00:07:18.450
There is a P wave,

173
00:07:18.450 --> 00:07:20.970
it's just that there's not a QRS that followed.

174
00:07:20.970 --> 00:07:23.490
When you see that, the next step is to go

175
00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:26.340
and look to see what the PR interval is looking like.

176
00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:29.760
Progressive PR lengthening, ultimately drop a beat.

177
00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:32.640
Second degree type one, I'm less concerned.

178
00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:34.710
PR interval is staying exactly the same,

179
00:07:34.710 --> 00:07:36.180
which is the case here.

180
00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:38.820
And now we simply have a non-conducted P.

181
00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:40.590
This is much more concerning.

182
00:07:40.590 --> 00:07:43.170
And these are ones that you do call cardiology about.

183
00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:45.780
As a matter of fact, if you're working inpatient medicine,

184
00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:48.330
you put the transcutaneous pacemaker on,

185
00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:51.120
put the stickers on as you're calling cardiology,

186
00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:52.950
and they'll say it's probably a type one

187
00:07:52.950 --> 00:07:54.540
and you'll say, "That's fine, still come look at them.

188
00:07:54.540 --> 00:07:55.620
We've got the stickers on."

189
00:07:55.620 --> 00:07:56.827
And then you're right and you're like,

190
00:07:56.827 --> 00:07:58.410
"No, it is a type two."

191
00:07:58.410 --> 00:08:00.390
These can progress to a third degree AV block,

192
00:08:00.390 --> 00:08:02.550
a complete heart block, without a lot of warning

193
00:08:02.550 --> 00:08:05.490
and then pacemaker may be necessary.

194
00:08:05.490 --> 00:08:09.570
So you only need to see one dropped beat to call this.

195
00:08:09.570 --> 00:08:11.700
You don't have to have, like, a whole string of them

196
00:08:11.700 --> 00:08:13.920
or sit back and wait for it to happen again.

197
00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:16.563
This is a huge, huge red flag when it happens.

198
00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:21.600
So third degree AV block messes people up a lot.

199
00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:25.680
And the reason is is that there are two independent rhythms.

200
00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:28.590
So we've got a ventricular rhythm which is typically slow

201
00:08:28.590 --> 00:08:30.540
and then we've got an atrial rhythm

202
00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:33.240
because in essence, the SA node doesn't realize

203
00:08:33.240 --> 00:08:34.887
that the ventricles aren't listening to it.

204
00:08:34.887 --> 00:08:37.890
The SA node continues to fire just like it normally does,

205
00:08:37.890 --> 00:08:39.540
ventricles depolarize.

206
00:08:39.540 --> 00:08:41.760
It's just that the connection between the atria

207
00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:43.560
and the ventricles is lost.

208
00:08:43.560 --> 00:08:45.840
So if you were to use calipers here,

209
00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:47.520
you could see here's P wave,

210
00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:49.920
there's another little P wave buried in the T.

211
00:08:49.920 --> 00:08:51.300
The T looks kind of funny.

212
00:08:51.300 --> 00:08:54.630
Here's another P, another P, another P, P, P.

213
00:08:54.630 --> 00:08:58.350
So you've basically got an atrial rhythm that's there

214
00:08:58.350 --> 00:08:59.880
and then a ventricular rhythm that's there

215
00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:02.190
and the two simply don't coincide.

216
00:09:02.190 --> 00:09:04.380
Why this becomes tricky is a lot of times people will want

217
00:09:04.380 --> 00:09:05.970
to try to connect

218
00:09:05.970 --> 00:09:08.010
and call this like a second degree type one

219
00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:11.250
because they'll say the distance between the P wave

220
00:09:11.250 --> 00:09:14.163
and the subsequent QRS complex is variable.

221
00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:17.130
Again, the variability is simply saying

222
00:09:17.130 --> 00:09:19.410
that the two just aren't connected at all.

223
00:09:19.410 --> 00:09:21.540
But you don't see progressive lengthening

224
00:09:21.540 --> 00:09:23.580
of the PR interval till you finally have a P wave

225
00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:26.100
that's non-conducted, that leaves a gap.

226
00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:28.380
Third degree AV blocks don't have a gap.

227
00:09:28.380 --> 00:09:31.053
The ventricles beat on their own just slowly.

228
00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:35.520
So again, if this comes along with an inferior MI

229
00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:37.680
and it's associated with AV nodal ischemia,

230
00:09:37.680 --> 00:09:39.330
that may recover.

231
00:09:39.330 --> 00:09:41.730
If this is associated with an anterior MI

232
00:09:41.730 --> 00:09:44.280
and a distal conducting system abnormality

233
00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:46.950
or distal conducting ischemia or damage,

234
00:09:46.950 --> 00:09:49.860
that generally doesn't recover and more often not than not,

235
00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:51.930
these end up with a pacemaker.

236
00:09:51.930 --> 00:09:53.640
The important thing is you'll see with pacemakers,

237
00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:56.970
you have to be able to correlate electrocardiographic

238
00:09:56.970 --> 00:10:00.090
or electrical abnormalities and symptoms.

239
00:10:00.090 --> 00:10:01.380
We actually had a patient,

240
00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:03.120
Dr. Levine, who you heard from earlier

241
00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:04.500
in the week is one of my colleagues.

242
00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:06.660
He had a patient who had a third degree AV block.

243
00:10:06.660 --> 00:10:08.160
This older woman who wanted nothing to do

244
00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:11.730
with this pacemaker thing and I think she's finally died,

245
00:10:11.730 --> 00:10:15.990
but she had a heart rate in the mid-40s for a long time.

246
00:10:15.990 --> 00:10:18.030
Felt fine, she didn't do a whole lot,

247
00:10:18.030 --> 00:10:20.640
it got her by, no interest in a pacemaker.

248
00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:24.000
It's like, "Okay, let us know if you get symptomatic."

249
00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:25.500
And she never did.

250
00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:28.140
I'm not sure exactly what she died of.

251
00:10:28.140 --> 00:10:31.083
So third degree AV block almost always needs a pacemaker.

252
00:10:32.340 --> 00:10:35.250
If it helps, this is how I mentally categorize

253
00:10:35.250 --> 00:10:38.370
or lump things together even though we've got,

254
00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:40.530
you know, second degree that's got a type one, type two.

255
00:10:40.530 --> 00:10:42.600
So we kind of have four blocks there.

256
00:10:42.600 --> 00:10:43.950
I lump a first degree AV block

257
00:10:43.950 --> 00:10:45.420
and a second degree type one

258
00:10:45.420 --> 00:10:48.030
into my I'm not terribly worried category.

259
00:10:48.030 --> 00:10:50.070
Second degree type two and third degree AV block

260
00:10:50.070 --> 00:10:52.590
I lump into my I'm very worried category.

261
00:10:52.590 --> 00:10:55.170
Time to call cardiology, may need a pacemaker.

262
00:10:55.170 --> 00:10:58.440
So if that helps you to kinda mentally categorize things,

263
00:10:58.440 --> 00:10:59.273
there you go.

264
00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:02.400
If I were to ask everyone what is this,

265
00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:04.010
everyone would say SVT.

266
00:11:04.010 --> 00:11:07.320
It is, supraventricular tachycardia though keep in mind

267
00:11:07.320 --> 00:11:09.750
that is a very broad category.

268
00:11:09.750 --> 00:11:11.910
A sinus rhythm of 101

269
00:11:11.910 --> 00:11:15.120
is technically an SVT, a supraventricular.

270
00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:16.680
It comes from above the ventricles

271
00:11:16.680 --> 00:11:19.200
and it is greater than 100 beats per minute.

272
00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:22.530
A heart rate of 101 that is sinus is an SVT.

273
00:11:22.530 --> 00:11:24.127
So even though we'll say,

274
00:11:24.127 --> 00:11:28.110
"Oh, this is SVT," thinking a little bit more narrowly

275
00:11:28.110 --> 00:11:30.840
that this is likely a reentrant tachycardia

276
00:11:30.840 --> 00:11:32.760
and I'll agree with you 100%

277
00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:37.760
but again the SVT nomenclature encompasses a lot of things.

278
00:11:38.130 --> 00:11:39.900
Atrial fibrillation, if it's the heart rate's

279
00:11:39.900 --> 00:11:41.790
above 100 is an SVT.

280
00:11:41.790 --> 00:11:43.500
A flutter if it's typically two

281
00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:46.950
to one conduction, heart rate's above 100, that is an SVT.

282
00:11:46.950 --> 00:11:48.950
So keep in mind that's a broad umbrella.

283
00:11:51.060 --> 00:11:53.430
If we're thinking paroxysmal SVT,

284
00:11:53.430 --> 00:11:56.640
this is typically a reentrant tachycardia

285
00:11:56.640 --> 00:11:57.480
and in essence,

286
00:11:57.480 --> 00:12:00.150
it's like you've got this little circular short circuit

287
00:12:00.150 --> 00:12:03.390
that involves the AV node and the atrium

288
00:12:03.390 --> 00:12:05.400
and basically goes round and round and round

289
00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.200
and just keeps peppering the ventricle

290
00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:11.880
with impulse after impulse to contract and contract it does.

291
00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:13.890
SVTs, in this case,

292
00:12:13.890 --> 00:12:15.870
like a reentrant tachycardia,

293
00:12:15.870 --> 00:12:19.170
rates typically in the 180 190, 200 range.

294
00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:21.150
They tend to go fairly fast.

295
00:12:21.150 --> 00:12:24.390
The paroxysmal part is just that it comes in paroxysms.

296
00:12:24.390 --> 00:12:26.850
It's like flipping on a light switch, everything's fine,

297
00:12:26.850 --> 00:12:27.820
you flip on the switch,

298
00:12:27.820 --> 00:12:28.653
(Jonathon vocalizing)

299
00:12:28.653 --> 00:12:30.120
the heart rate goes real fast,

300
00:12:31.470 --> 00:12:32.640
a lot of times people will cough

301
00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:33.570
or they'll do something else

302
00:12:33.570 --> 00:12:36.900
that increases vagal tone somewhat inadvertently

303
00:12:36.900 --> 00:12:39.690
and then it converts and then they go back

304
00:12:39.690 --> 00:12:41.640
to sinus conduction.

305
00:12:41.640 --> 00:12:44.590
So a lot of times, it can be triggered by a premature beat.

306
00:12:45.450 --> 00:12:46.680
AV nodal reentrant tachycardia

307
00:12:46.680 --> 00:12:49.170
versus AV reentrant tachycardia.

308
00:12:49.170 --> 00:12:51.390
The differentiation is not that critical.

309
00:12:51.390 --> 00:12:53.760
Simply know that it is a short circuit pathway

310
00:12:53.760 --> 00:12:56.973
that's for the electrophysiologist to figure out for us.

311
00:12:58.080 --> 00:12:58.913
All right, question three.

312
00:12:58.913 --> 00:13:00.450
We've got a 24-year-old woman

313
00:13:00.450 --> 00:13:02.940
with a history of panic disorder presents to the ED

314
00:13:02.940 --> 00:13:04.920
with a heart rate of 180 beats a minute

315
00:13:04.920 --> 00:13:07.110
without clear atrial activity.

316
00:13:07.110 --> 00:13:11.280
The strip may look just like the one we saw, BP 130 over 80.

317
00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:12.450
She reports feeling anxious

318
00:13:12.450 --> 00:13:14.970
but does not have any dizziness or chest pain.

319
00:13:14.970 --> 00:13:18.510
You diagnose assuming paroxysmal SVT,

320
00:13:18.510 --> 00:13:19.998
you try vagal maneuvers

321
00:13:19.998 --> 00:13:21.240
'cause you gotta do something

322
00:13:21.240 --> 00:13:23.490
while you're getting an IV in, right?

323
00:13:23.490 --> 00:13:25.950
Doesn't change the rhythm or rate,

324
00:13:25.950 --> 00:13:28.740
usually it doesn't, but if it does, what a cool thing.

325
00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:30.810
It's like you're healing someone with your hands,

326
00:13:30.810 --> 00:13:34.320
you know, take a big breath in and bear down and they'll go.

327
00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:35.970
It's like, "No, no, no, bear down

328
00:13:35.970 --> 00:13:37.530
like you're pushing a cow out of your bottom.

329
00:13:37.530 --> 00:13:39.150
I want you to push hard."

330
00:13:39.150 --> 00:13:41.850
And if you check your own pulse and do that,

331
00:13:41.850 --> 00:13:44.610
bear down super hard, you will slow your heart rate down.

332
00:13:44.610 --> 00:13:46.140
Unilateral carotid massage.

333
00:13:46.140 --> 00:13:46.973
We don't do bilateral

334
00:13:46.973 --> 00:13:49.380
because you can actually overdo the stimulation

335
00:13:49.380 --> 00:13:52.710
of the vagal nerve and end up with a significant block.

336
00:13:52.710 --> 00:13:55.110
But if you keep in mind the carotid baroreceptors are right

337
00:13:55.110 --> 00:13:56.670
at the carotid bifurcation.

338
00:13:56.670 --> 00:13:59.677
So gently massaging the carotid baroreceptor says,

339
00:13:59.677 --> 00:14:00.900
"Blood pressure is super high,

340
00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:02.580
let's slow things down just a bit."

341
00:14:02.580 --> 00:14:04.350
And sometimes you can actually block

342
00:14:04.350 --> 00:14:07.560
down a supraventricular tachycardia,

343
00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:09.060
but we'll say none of that worked.

344
00:14:09.060 --> 00:14:10.293
So what do you do next?

345
00:14:11.310 --> 00:14:12.143
Next best step.

346
00:14:12.143 --> 00:14:15.450
We've got adenosine, amiodarone, diltiazem,

347
00:14:15.450 --> 00:14:18.690
or better living through electricity.

348
00:14:18.690 --> 00:14:19.540
Let's cardiovert.

349
00:14:21.990 --> 00:14:24.000
Keeping in mind someone

350
00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.280
who's hemodynamically stable, feeling well

351
00:14:26.280 --> 00:14:28.263
just has a fast heart rate.

352
00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:35.160
AMI adenosine.

353
00:14:35.160 --> 00:14:37.170
All right, wonderful.

354
00:14:37.170 --> 00:14:39.450
Have you ever gotten to use adenosine?

355
00:14:39.450 --> 00:14:41.430
Isn't it fun because you get

356
00:14:41.430 --> 00:14:43.657
at least a full screen of flat line, you're like,

357
00:14:43.657 --> 00:14:45.840
"Huh, I wonder if it's gonna restart."

358
00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:46.890
And it always does

359
00:14:46.890 --> 00:14:49.200
because adenosine disappears really quickly.

360
00:14:49.200 --> 00:14:51.607
But it's kind of like an electrical pause that it's like,

361
00:14:51.607 --> 00:14:53.040
"All right, let's take a break here.

362
00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:55.830
Slow down, let's relax."

363
00:14:55.830 --> 00:14:58.050
So adenosine is cool stuff.

364
00:14:58.050 --> 00:14:59.190
Six milligram bolus.

365
00:14:59.190 --> 00:15:01.170
It's not like a slow gentle push.

366
00:15:01.170 --> 00:15:03.480
You want it to come through as a bolus.

367
00:15:03.480 --> 00:15:05.130
12 milligrams is the follow-up dose.

368
00:15:05.130 --> 00:15:06.990
If you don't convert with 12 milligrams

369
00:15:06.990 --> 00:15:10.410
of adenosine, abandon adenosine and do something else,

370
00:15:10.410 --> 00:15:12.240
either metoprolol.

371
00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:13.950
Diltiazem versus verapamil seems

372
00:15:13.950 --> 00:15:16.740
to be more institution-specific.

373
00:15:16.740 --> 00:15:19.380
We use diltiazem exclusively in our institution.

374
00:15:19.380 --> 00:15:22.650
I don't know if we even probably stock IV verapamil.

375
00:15:22.650 --> 00:15:23.913
It just never gets used.

376
00:15:25.380 --> 00:15:27.720
If you inadvertently give adenosine

377
00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:32.160
or a AV nodal blocking drug like a beta blocker

378
00:15:32.160 --> 00:15:34.470
or diltiazem to someone who,

379
00:15:34.470 --> 00:15:36.180
oh goodness, you mistook this

380
00:15:36.180 --> 00:15:38.610
and it's just sinus tachycardia,

381
00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:41.130
you'll cause a gradual slowing in heart rate.

382
00:15:41.130 --> 00:15:42.780
Whereas a reentrant tachycardia,

383
00:15:42.780 --> 00:15:46.380
which is due to a short circuit pathway, converts abruptly.

384
00:15:46.380 --> 00:15:47.760
So it can be helpful.

385
00:15:47.760 --> 00:15:50.880
The mode of conversion back to a slower heart rate

386
00:15:50.880 --> 00:15:53.100
or back to sinus rhythm can be helpful

387
00:15:53.100 --> 00:15:55.950
as well in diagnosing what's there.

388
00:15:55.950 --> 00:15:59.160
You can use digoxin but it takes a long time to load.

389
00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:02.703
It eventually will work, but it doesn't work quickly.

390
00:16:04.470 --> 00:16:07.410
Long-term therapy, typically you'll use the drug

391
00:16:07.410 --> 00:16:11.280
that converted the rhythm, assuming that wasn't adenosine

392
00:16:11.280 --> 00:16:12.930
'cause you can't really do oral adenosine

393
00:16:12.930 --> 00:16:15.750
or carry an IV adenosine bolus around with you

394
00:16:15.750 --> 00:16:18.150
to just squirt in periodically when this happens.

395
00:16:18.150 --> 00:16:20.880
So diltiazem, any of the beta blockers,

396
00:16:20.880 --> 00:16:21.713
especially the ones

397
00:16:21.713 --> 00:16:25.113
without intrinsic sympathomimetic activity are reasonable.

398
00:16:26.460 --> 00:16:27.690
I'm not gonna prescribe flecainide.

399
00:16:27.690 --> 00:16:29.970
I will leave that to our electrophysiologist.

400
00:16:29.970 --> 00:16:31.980
Most of these patients end up with EP,

401
00:16:31.980 --> 00:16:33.660
most end up with a catheter ablation

402
00:16:33.660 --> 00:16:35.163
as opposed to medical therapy.

403
00:16:37.560 --> 00:16:40.110
MAT simply be aware of.

404
00:16:40.110 --> 00:16:41.940
Fortunately the name says it all.

405
00:16:41.940 --> 00:16:45.060
It's multifocal atrial tachycardia.

406
00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:46.350
The multifocal part implies

407
00:16:46.350 --> 00:16:48.750
that you've got multiple different atrial foci

408
00:16:48.750 --> 00:16:51.990
that can fire meaning what'll happen is you get P waves

409
00:16:51.990 --> 00:16:53.760
of different morphology.

410
00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:55.890
So if you've got two atria here

411
00:16:55.890 --> 00:16:58.320
and the SA node sits high up in the right atrium,

412
00:16:58.320 --> 00:17:01.920
if he happen to have a focus of atrial depolarization

413
00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:04.020
that's really close to the SA node,

414
00:17:04.020 --> 00:17:07.140
the P wave's gonna look like the P wave normally looks.

415
00:17:07.140 --> 00:17:09.320
On the other hand, if you've got a focus way over here

416
00:17:09.320 --> 00:17:12.210
on the other side of the left atrium that fires,

417
00:17:12.210 --> 00:17:15.330
it's gonna create a very different looking P wave.

418
00:17:15.330 --> 00:17:16.410
So one of the hallmarks

419
00:17:16.410 --> 00:17:19.170
or the hallmark of MAT is if you look closely,

420
00:17:19.170 --> 00:17:21.750
you got a bunch of different looking P waves.

421
00:17:21.750 --> 00:17:22.650
They're still P waves.

422
00:17:22.650 --> 00:17:25.560
It's just that they're not all consistent.

423
00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:27.480
This one tends to be a little bit irregular,

424
00:17:27.480 --> 00:17:30.123
sometimes gets mistaken for atrial fibrillation.

425
00:17:31.290 --> 00:17:34.560
Basically an AV nodal slowing drug is helpful here.

426
00:17:34.560 --> 00:17:36.060
And one of the important things is

427
00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:37.860
that this will almost always be associated

428
00:17:37.860 --> 00:17:40.110
with someone who has severe pulmonary disease.

429
00:17:40.110 --> 00:17:42.810
So if the stem of the question describes someone who's got,

430
00:17:42.810 --> 00:17:44.250
you know, severe COPD

431
00:17:44.250 --> 00:17:47.160
and now they've got a rhythm strip that looks like this,

432
00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:48.990
or a description that sounds like this,

433
00:17:48.990 --> 00:17:52.563
think MAT and that would be the the diagnosis.

434
00:17:54.570 --> 00:17:55.590
AFib.

435
00:17:55.590 --> 00:17:58.170
I don't have to tell you a whole lot about diagnosing that.

436
00:17:58.170 --> 00:18:00.810
The one thing I will point out is if you're tempted

437
00:18:00.810 --> 00:18:03.600
to say atrial fib slash flutter

438
00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:05.700
because you look at the rhythm strip

439
00:18:05.700 --> 00:18:08.400
and say, "Well, it does look like AFib

440
00:18:08.400 --> 00:18:12.480
but maybe this right here could be a couple of P waves."

441
00:18:12.480 --> 00:18:15.330
Okay fine, call it AFib slash flutter.

442
00:18:15.330 --> 00:18:16.680
It doesn't really matter much.

443
00:18:16.680 --> 00:18:19.380
You still treat it as atrial fibrillation.

444
00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:22.410
Bottom line is that in the chaos of atrial fibrillation,

445
00:18:22.410 --> 00:18:25.500
sometimes you'll see a little bit of rhythmic organization,

446
00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:28.260
you know, kind of the opposite of entropy

447
00:18:28.260 --> 00:18:30.660
and you may see something that looks kinda like a P wave.

448
00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:32.970
If you're tempted to say that, step back

449
00:18:32.970 --> 00:18:34.470
and look at the rhythm strip as a whole

450
00:18:34.470 --> 00:18:37.440
and say, "Okay as a whole there is nothing significant there

451
00:18:37.440 --> 00:18:39.000
as far as atrial activity.

452
00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.367
It is all scattered and variable."

453
00:18:42.360 --> 00:18:45.360
There are terms that paroxysmal versus permanent.

454
00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:48.630
Permanent is simply a term that means we've decided

455
00:18:48.630 --> 00:18:51.090
to stop trying to convert this.

456
00:18:51.090 --> 00:18:53.250
We're just gonna declare you got atrial fibrillation,

457
00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:55.770
we're not gonna keep trying to convert this.

458
00:18:55.770 --> 00:18:57.120
It's gonna be there always.

459
00:18:57.120 --> 00:19:00.030
So permanent is not really an electrocardiographic finding.

460
00:19:00.030 --> 00:19:02.250
Permanent simply says we've stepped back

461
00:19:02.250 --> 00:19:04.590
and are gonna just let this happen.

462
00:19:04.590 --> 00:19:07.080
All right, so we've got a 76-year-old man

463
00:19:07.080 --> 00:19:09.720
who's into your office with new atrial fibrillation,

464
00:19:09.720 --> 00:19:12.660
rate of 130, BP's 130 over 80.

465
00:19:12.660 --> 00:19:14.520
He also has COPD from smoking

466
00:19:14.520 --> 00:19:17.670
and uses an albuterol inhaler, inhaled corticosteroids.

467
00:19:17.670 --> 00:19:20.403
He's got some wheezes and rhonchi on exam.

468
00:19:22.109 --> 00:19:25.080
So which of the following would be the best choice

469
00:19:25.080 --> 00:19:26.973
to control his heart rate?

470
00:19:28.710 --> 00:19:30.760
We've got digoxin, diltiazem, propanolol.

471
00:19:32.370 --> 00:19:34.590
And you could almost use any beta blocker there

472
00:19:34.590 --> 00:19:37.713
if you don't like propanolol, or electrical cardioversion.

473
00:19:43.410 --> 00:19:44.910
So most are going with diltiazem.

474
00:19:44.910 --> 00:19:47.670
Excellent and a beta blocker

475
00:19:47.670 --> 00:19:48.900
would've been a reasonable choice.

476
00:19:48.900 --> 00:19:51.760
But I hear probably some concern about the COPD

477
00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:55.710
and are we gonna complicate the COPD management

478
00:19:55.710 --> 00:19:58.210
with the drug that we're using for rate reduction?

479
00:19:59.220 --> 00:20:04.220
So going back even to 2002 was a fairly landmark trial,

480
00:20:04.680 --> 00:20:07.140
the AFFIRM trial, that basically tried

481
00:20:07.140 --> 00:20:10.560
to answer the question which is better: rhythm control,

482
00:20:10.560 --> 00:20:12.540
meaning trying to convert someone from AFib

483
00:20:12.540 --> 00:20:15.360
back to sinus rhythm, or rate control,

484
00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:16.440
leaving the AFib alone

485
00:20:16.440 --> 00:20:18.330
and simply trying to decrease heart rate.

486
00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:21.450
And the bottom line is that it didn't make any difference.

487
00:20:21.450 --> 00:20:24.930
And we all recognize that we may have a patient

488
00:20:24.930 --> 00:20:27.000
who completely doesn't tolerate being

489
00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:28.290
in atrial fibrillation,

490
00:20:28.290 --> 00:20:31.530
therefore, rhythm control is better for that individual.

491
00:20:31.530 --> 00:20:35.250
And we may find someone who does not tolerate the drugs

492
00:20:35.250 --> 00:20:36.870
that keep them in sinus rhythm

493
00:20:36.870 --> 00:20:38.700
and in that case, rate control may be better

494
00:20:38.700 --> 00:20:39.960
for that individual.

495
00:20:39.960 --> 00:20:43.710
So granted there are individuals who will have a preference,

496
00:20:43.710 --> 00:20:45.270
whether it's a personal preference

497
00:20:45.270 --> 00:20:47.490
or medical preference for one or the other.

498
00:20:47.490 --> 00:20:49.530
But when you look at large populations,

499
00:20:49.530 --> 00:20:50.850
rate control versus rhythm control

500
00:20:50.850 --> 00:20:52.770
are considered equivalent.

501
00:20:52.770 --> 00:20:55.650
So we can use the dihydropyridine

502
00:20:55.650 --> 00:20:57.960
the non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers.

503
00:20:57.960 --> 00:21:00.058
Diltiazem is the typically the drug of choice

504
00:21:00.058 --> 00:21:02.910
if you're not wanting to use a beta blocker.

505
00:21:02.910 --> 00:21:04.545
Keep in mind beta blockers do a better job

506
00:21:04.545 --> 00:21:07.170
of controlling rate, not just at rest,

507
00:21:07.170 --> 00:21:09.060
but also with activity.

508
00:21:09.060 --> 00:21:12.990
Diltiazem does a better job of controlling rate at rest.

509
00:21:12.990 --> 00:21:15.810
It tends to work less well when someone is more active

510
00:21:15.810 --> 00:21:18.510
and that's the trigger for their increased heart rate.

511
00:21:20.550 --> 00:21:22.680
The next question once we've decided

512
00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:24.480
on rate versus rhythm control is,

513
00:21:24.480 --> 00:21:27.540
okay, what to do about anticoagulation?

514
00:21:27.540 --> 00:21:29.220
What about stroke risk?

515
00:21:29.220 --> 00:21:32.460
In essence, risks ratification on both sides,

516
00:21:32.460 --> 00:21:33.870
both the risk of stroke

517
00:21:33.870 --> 00:21:37.050
and the risk of bleeding with anticoagulation,

518
00:21:37.050 --> 00:21:38.460
both are important and our job is

519
00:21:38.460 --> 00:21:40.620
to weigh the risks versus the benefits.

520
00:21:40.620 --> 00:21:44.760
And we have risk assessment schemes

521
00:21:44.760 --> 00:21:46.230
for both of those.

522
00:21:46.230 --> 00:21:49.740
The CHADS2 score is now fully replaced by CHADS2-VASc.

523
00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:51.060
I'll show you that in just a second.

524
00:21:51.060 --> 00:21:53.670
And then we counter that with the HAS-BLED score,

525
00:21:53.670 --> 00:21:55.470
which gives us a rough idea

526
00:21:55.470 --> 00:21:57.030
of what's this person's bleeding risk

527
00:21:57.030 --> 00:21:58.530
and how can we weigh this out.

528
00:22:00.330 --> 00:22:02.550
So here are the elements of CHADS2-VASc

529
00:22:02.550 --> 00:22:04.890
and if you don't remember those,

530
00:22:04.890 --> 00:22:07.590
you should have a medical calculator on your device

531
00:22:07.590 --> 00:22:09.660
that you carry in your pocket at all times

532
00:22:09.660 --> 00:22:11.390
and it will have the CHADS2-VASc score.

533
00:22:11.390 --> 00:22:12.870
So if you don't remember the numbers,

534
00:22:12.870 --> 00:22:16.320
you can use a little calculator to figure them up.

535
00:22:16.320 --> 00:22:17.670
So as you can see, you get points

536
00:22:17.670 --> 00:22:21.120
for heart failure, hypertension, age.

537
00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:22.770
So the difference between CHADS2

538
00:22:22.770 --> 00:22:26.550
and CHADS2-VASc, CHADS2-VASc now adds a point

539
00:22:26.550 --> 00:22:31.550
for 65 to 74, 2 points for 75 and above,

540
00:22:31.620 --> 00:22:34.500
you still get a point for diabetes, two points for stroke.

541
00:22:34.500 --> 00:22:36.000
So if you've done this in the past,

542
00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:38.970
then there's a greater risk you're gonna do it again.

543
00:22:38.970 --> 00:22:42.540
Vascular disease is kind of an all encompassing term

544
00:22:42.540 --> 00:22:44.280
and it's a little bit subjective.

545
00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:46.590
And then unfortunately,

546
00:22:46.590 --> 00:22:49.260
women with atrial fibrillation have a greater stroke risk

547
00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:51.090
than men with atrial fibrillation.

548
00:22:51.090 --> 00:22:54.060
So unfortunately, women get an extra point

549
00:22:54.060 --> 00:22:55.563
on the CHADS2-VASc score.

550
00:22:57.720 --> 00:22:59.280
We basically take the score

551
00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:01.767
and that gives an idea or estimation

552
00:23:01.767 --> 00:23:04.590
of what someone's stroke risk is.

553
00:23:04.590 --> 00:23:08.130
Please don't take these numbers right here as the gospel

554
00:23:08.130 --> 00:23:10.350
and don't memorize those numbers.

555
00:23:10.350 --> 00:23:12.000
The reason is is that the,

556
00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:16.110
when the scoring scheme is applied to different populations

557
00:23:16.110 --> 00:23:18.810
with variable stroke risk at baseline,

558
00:23:18.810 --> 00:23:21.060
the numbers are gonna pan out differently.

559
00:23:21.060 --> 00:23:24.690
So it's not so much memorize these numbers right here,

560
00:23:24.690 --> 00:23:26.347
but recognize that a CHADS2 score of,

561
00:23:26.347 --> 00:23:28.410
or CHADS2-VASc score of two

562
00:23:28.410 --> 00:23:30.810
or above equals anticoagulation.

563
00:23:30.810 --> 00:23:34.380
In all populations, the risk of anticoagulation

564
00:23:34.380 --> 00:23:36.030
is outweighed by the benefit

565
00:23:36.030 --> 00:23:38.790
of anticoagulation and the decrease in stroke risk.

566
00:23:38.790 --> 00:23:43.200
CHADS2-VASc score of one is challenging,

567
00:23:43.200 --> 00:23:46.683
especially if the only point is for female sex.

568
00:23:47.700 --> 00:23:50.400
That's one where if you happen to find someone

569
00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:53.880
who truly has a score of one, aspirin is still an option.

570
00:23:53.880 --> 00:23:55.683
Anticoagulation is preferred.

571
00:23:57.570 --> 00:23:59.160
So what about anticoagulation?

572
00:23:59.160 --> 00:24:02.523
Warfarin is becoming a thing of the pas it seems.

573
00:24:03.420 --> 00:24:04.253
Kind of sad.

574
00:24:04.253 --> 00:24:05.880
I mean, I kind of miss dosing warfarin.

575
00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:08.040
It's sort of fun to tinker with it.

576
00:24:08.040 --> 00:24:10.200
I know some people say, "No, I don't miss that at all."

577
00:24:10.200 --> 00:24:12.750
But if you kind of enjoy, that's sort of like, you know,

578
00:24:12.750 --> 00:24:15.450
dosing unfractionated heparin, you know, as a resident,

579
00:24:15.450 --> 00:24:16.830
you know, call up with the PTT

580
00:24:16.830 --> 00:24:18.753
and stuff, kinda miss that too.

581
00:24:19.680 --> 00:24:22.020
So we don't say NOAC anymore,

582
00:24:22.020 --> 00:24:24.330
which is novel oral anticoagulant.

583
00:24:24.330 --> 00:24:26.160
It's now DOAC, which is direct.

584
00:24:26.160 --> 00:24:28.200
They're no longer novel drugs.

585
00:24:28.200 --> 00:24:30.480
If you have trouble remembering which drug does what

586
00:24:30.480 --> 00:24:31.950
because there are four,

587
00:24:31.950 --> 00:24:34.500
dabigatran is the only direct thrombin inhibitor

588
00:24:34.500 --> 00:24:37.380
and then the 10A inhibitors all have,

589
00:24:37.380 --> 00:24:39.090
and I'm sure it was intentional,

590
00:24:39.090 --> 00:24:41.730
all have Xa or 10A in their name.

591
00:24:41.730 --> 00:24:44.730
So if you ever struggle to remember which one does what,

592
00:24:44.730 --> 00:24:47.460
the 10A inhibitors have given you a handy clue

593
00:24:47.460 --> 00:24:49.803
by including Xa in their names.

594
00:24:51.390 --> 00:24:54.990
Which is better among the three 10A inhibitors?

595
00:24:54.990 --> 00:24:57.810
Again, it's going to depend, there's no head-to-head study

596
00:24:57.810 --> 00:25:00.060
and it's all gonna depend on the trial that you look at

597
00:25:00.060 --> 00:25:02.880
and how each trial carves down different subsets

598
00:25:02.880 --> 00:25:05.460
of patients to say, "In this little subset

599
00:25:05.460 --> 00:25:07.080
with these characteristics,

600
00:25:07.080 --> 00:25:09.240
this drug outperformed that drug."

601
00:25:09.240 --> 00:25:12.360
But there's no broad data to say head to head one

602
00:25:12.360 --> 00:25:15.330
of these drugs is clearly superior to the other.

603
00:25:15.330 --> 00:25:17.580
Do keep in mind they have the same

604
00:25:17.580 --> 00:25:19.680
bleeding risk as warfarin.

605
00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:22.747
And again, there are studies that will say,

606
00:25:22.747 --> 00:25:24.690
"Well, in this tiny population,

607
00:25:24.690 --> 00:25:26.760
this one had a lower bleeding risk than warfarin.

608
00:25:26.760 --> 00:25:29.580
Across the board, we consider the bleeding risk equivalent."

609
00:25:29.580 --> 00:25:30.413
I think that's important

610
00:25:30.413 --> 00:25:31.920
to make sure your patients understand that

611
00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:34.200
because the ads on TV, for example,

612
00:25:34.200 --> 00:25:37.350
seem to suggest that this is a safer alternative

613
00:25:37.350 --> 00:25:38.370
to warfarin.

614
00:25:38.370 --> 00:25:39.203
Really, it's not.

615
00:25:39.203 --> 00:25:40.770
It's still an anticoagulant.

616
00:25:40.770 --> 00:25:42.000
Granted, you don't have to monitor it,

617
00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.580
but that doesn't make it less safe or more safe.

618
00:25:44.580 --> 00:25:45.570
It simply says you don't have

619
00:25:45.570 --> 00:25:48.390
to monitor the efficacy of it.

620
00:25:48.390 --> 00:25:50.207
We do adjust the dose in renal disease

621
00:25:50.207 --> 00:25:54.573
and thankfully, we have IV antidotes for all four drugs now.

622
00:25:56.430 --> 00:25:58.650
So what if we're only looking at rhythm control

623
00:25:58.650 --> 00:26:01.680
'cause step one is identification of atrial fibrillation.

624
00:26:01.680 --> 00:26:03.780
Step two is controlling rate.

625
00:26:03.780 --> 00:26:07.710
And then step three is now we decided anticoagulation.

626
00:26:07.710 --> 00:26:08.790
But what if we get to step four

627
00:26:08.790 --> 00:26:10.830
and say we truly wanna convert this person

628
00:26:10.830 --> 00:26:13.130
from atrial fibrillation back to sinus rhythm.

629
00:26:14.040 --> 00:26:15.870
If someone is hemodynamically unstable,

630
00:26:15.870 --> 00:26:18.210
cardioversion is an option.

631
00:26:18.210 --> 00:26:20.070
If they're not unstable,

632
00:26:20.070 --> 00:26:22.290
then make sure they're anticoagulated first.

633
00:26:22.290 --> 00:26:24.060
Again, this is typically not in our purview,

634
00:26:24.060 --> 00:26:26.250
but you ought to be aware of the sequence here.

635
00:26:26.250 --> 00:26:27.240
There are a bunch of drugs

636
00:26:27.240 --> 00:26:30.330
that we don't often use for pharmacologic conversion.

637
00:26:30.330 --> 00:26:34.500
Amiodarone we recognize even though it's being used

638
00:26:34.500 --> 00:26:36.570
so much more frequently now.

639
00:26:36.570 --> 00:26:38.100
I think back to when I was a resident

640
00:26:38.100 --> 00:26:39.600
and it was kind of like Voldemort.

641
00:26:39.600 --> 00:26:41.670
I mean, you just didn't say amiodarone.

642
00:26:41.670 --> 00:26:43.499
It's like, "We're gonna use amiodarone",

643
00:26:43.499 --> 00:26:45.480
and you know, then it's, like, in hushed tones

644
00:26:45.480 --> 00:26:46.980
and everybody in the room gets silent.

645
00:26:46.980 --> 00:26:48.930
And now it's like, "Oh, we're gonna start amiodarone.

646
00:26:48.930 --> 00:26:50.070
Fine."

647
00:26:50.070 --> 00:26:52.350
But do recognize it can cause thyroid abnormalities

648
00:26:52.350 --> 00:26:54.483
and cause interstitial lung disease.

649
00:26:55.860 --> 00:26:57.030
Catheter ablation.

650
00:26:57.030 --> 00:27:00.270
Again, we'll leave to our EP colleagues.

651
00:27:00.270 --> 00:27:04.320
Basically what happens is the disordered left atrium

652
00:27:04.320 --> 00:27:08.400
is targeted and in essence, is ablated

653
00:27:08.400 --> 00:27:11.040
so that the conduction through it becomes less good

654
00:27:11.040 --> 00:27:13.050
and the conduction then preferentially comes

655
00:27:13.050 --> 00:27:14.133
from the SA node.

656
00:27:16.110 --> 00:27:18.690
That may be described as a maze procedure

657
00:27:18.690 --> 00:27:21.330
or left atrial appendage obliteration

658
00:27:21.330 --> 00:27:23.455
that's generally done if the patient is going

659
00:27:23.455 --> 00:27:26.160
in for surgery for other reasons.

660
00:27:26.160 --> 00:27:28.050
You've probably seen more of your patients going

661
00:27:28.050 --> 00:27:30.480
to get a watchman device placed.

662
00:27:30.480 --> 00:27:31.920
It is a really cool, little device.

663
00:27:31.920 --> 00:27:34.110
It's sort of like an IVC filter

664
00:27:34.110 --> 00:27:35.760
except it doesn't actually filter blood.

665
00:27:35.760 --> 00:27:38.280
It obliterates the left atrial appendage.

666
00:27:38.280 --> 00:27:40.530
The interesting thing though is the left atrial appendage

667
00:27:40.530 --> 00:27:43.140
is obviously on the left side of the heart.

668
00:27:43.140 --> 00:27:45.060
This is a transcatheter approach

669
00:27:45.060 --> 00:27:46.710
that comes on the venous side.

670
00:27:46.710 --> 00:27:49.320
So in order to get from the right atrium

671
00:27:49.320 --> 00:27:50.490
over to the left atrium,

672
00:27:50.490 --> 00:27:53.280
they gotta puncture through the atrial septum.

673
00:27:53.280 --> 00:27:54.720
It's really an interesting procedure.

674
00:27:54.720 --> 00:27:55.805
So it comes up on the venous side,

675
00:27:55.805 --> 00:27:58.200
on the right side, punctures through the septum,

676
00:27:58.200 --> 00:28:00.150
which actually gives apparently the best aim

677
00:28:00.150 --> 00:28:02.100
over to the left atrial appendage.

678
00:28:02.100 --> 00:28:04.050
The subtle balloon device is deployed

679
00:28:04.050 --> 00:28:05.550
into the left atrial appendage

680
00:28:05.550 --> 00:28:08.370
and once successfully deployed,

681
00:28:08.370 --> 00:28:12.300
basically, it obviates the need for anticoagulation.

682
00:28:12.300 --> 00:28:14.280
So a very cool device we ought to be aware

683
00:28:14.280 --> 00:28:15.963
at least of how it works.

684
00:28:17.070 --> 00:28:18.660
I love atrial flutter

685
00:28:18.660 --> 00:28:21.213
just because it's so much fun on EKGs.

686
00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:26.190
Remember flutter is always described as a ratio.

687
00:28:26.190 --> 00:28:30.450
So it's a ratio of flutter waves to ventricular response.

688
00:28:30.450 --> 00:28:31.860
Flutter waves typically run

689
00:28:31.860 --> 00:28:34.890
in the high 200s to 300 rate.

690
00:28:34.890 --> 00:28:36.480
So in theory, if you had atrial flutter

691
00:28:36.480 --> 00:28:38.430
with a one to one conduction,

692
00:28:38.430 --> 00:28:41.580
you would have a heart rate of around 300.

693
00:28:41.580 --> 00:28:43.230
A flutter with a two to one conduction,

694
00:28:43.230 --> 00:28:45.330
every other flutter wave gets through.

695
00:28:45.330 --> 00:28:48.960
Heart rate typically the mid-130s up to around 150.

696
00:28:48.960 --> 00:28:50.400
And this is important enough

697
00:28:50.400 --> 00:28:52.260
that if you see someone in clinic

698
00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:53.850
and they're sitting there, you know,

699
00:28:53.850 --> 00:28:56.430
hopefully asymptomatic and hemodynamically stable

700
00:28:56.430 --> 00:28:58.290
with a heart rate in the mid-130s

701
00:28:58.290 --> 00:29:01.470
and it is very, very, very consistent,

702
00:29:01.470 --> 00:29:03.690
you ought to be thinking to yourself, take a step back.

703
00:29:03.690 --> 00:29:06.600
Is this a flutter with a two to one conduction?

704
00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:10.500
Had a recent patient of mine who came in

705
00:29:10.500 --> 00:29:13.470
with a heart rate in the mid-130s and our med tech

706
00:29:13.470 --> 00:29:15.780
or our nursing assistant rather

707
00:29:15.780 --> 00:29:17.340
who's now gonna be in our medical school

708
00:29:17.340 --> 00:29:18.930
so I'm very happy,

709
00:29:18.930 --> 00:29:22.530
had, you know, the brains to say, "His heart rate's 130,

710
00:29:22.530 --> 00:29:24.330
would you like me to get an EKG?"

711
00:29:24.330 --> 00:29:25.470
Heck yes I would.

712
00:29:25.470 --> 00:29:27.270
And how was he feeling?

713
00:29:27.270 --> 00:29:29.490
He didn't even know his heart rate was 130.

714
00:29:29.490 --> 00:29:31.020
The guy was in his mid-80s

715
00:29:31.020 --> 00:29:33.120
with a heart rate in the mid-130s.

716
00:29:33.120 --> 00:29:36.240
So he had a flutter with a two to one conduction.

717
00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:38.340
Two to one conduction, which is what you see right up here,

718
00:29:38.340 --> 00:29:39.870
the heart rate right around 150,

719
00:29:39.870 --> 00:29:42.330
is fairly difficult to recognize,

720
00:29:42.330 --> 00:29:44.340
because you don't actually see flutter waves,

721
00:29:44.340 --> 00:29:46.710
you just see a compilation flutter wave

722
00:29:46.710 --> 00:29:49.800
and T wave in between each QRS complex.

723
00:29:49.800 --> 00:29:52.560
But if you can slow the ventricular response

724
00:29:52.560 --> 00:29:55.200
down a little bit, like do a vagal maneuver,

725
00:29:55.200 --> 00:29:58.500
once you hit a three to one or lower conduction,

726
00:29:58.500 --> 00:30:00.300
typically, flutter waves are a lot easier to see,

727
00:30:00.300 --> 00:30:02.613
but two to one conduction is hard to pick up.

728
00:30:04.020 --> 00:30:04.980
And again, we manage that

729
00:30:04.980 --> 00:30:07.410
just as we would atrial fibrillation.

730
00:30:07.410 --> 00:30:08.243
All right, next question.

731
00:30:08.243 --> 00:30:10.800
We've got a 32-year-old woman who presents with dyspnea,

732
00:30:10.800 --> 00:30:12.930
palpitations, and near syncope.

733
00:30:12.930 --> 00:30:15.690
EKG shows, here's the key findings,

734
00:30:15.690 --> 00:30:18.723
AFib at 150 with delta waves.

735
00:30:19.800 --> 00:30:20.880
Which one of the following treatments

736
00:30:20.880 --> 00:30:24.270
is a class one recommendation for acute treatment?

737
00:30:24.270 --> 00:30:25.787
So what's the diagnosis?

738
00:30:25.787 --> 00:30:30.300
And once you know that, what do you wanna do with the AFib

739
00:30:30.300 --> 00:30:33.300
with rapid ventricular response?

740
00:30:33.300 --> 00:30:36.667
So we got metoprolol, diltiazem, dig, and procainamide.

741
00:30:42.420 --> 00:30:44.760
So almost a, well, a majority

742
00:30:44.760 --> 00:30:48.060
but not quite 50% are going with procainamide.

743
00:30:48.060 --> 00:30:49.053
Nicely done.

744
00:30:50.460 --> 00:30:53.130
The description delta wave should make you think

745
00:30:53.130 --> 00:30:54.660
this is pre-excitation.

746
00:30:54.660 --> 00:30:57.090
The prototype is Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome.

747
00:30:57.090 --> 00:30:59.070
And if you're an epidem geek,

748
00:30:59.070 --> 00:31:03.990
it's the bundle of Kent that is the bypass pathway in WPW.

749
00:31:03.990 --> 00:31:06.150
But WPW is a prototype.

750
00:31:06.150 --> 00:31:08.730
There are multiple pre-excitation syndromes

751
00:31:08.730 --> 00:31:12.420
and multiple pre-excitation pathways that can develop.

752
00:31:12.420 --> 00:31:14.400
The things that you're looking for.

753
00:31:14.400 --> 00:31:16.890
One is a short PR interval

754
00:31:16.890 --> 00:31:19.140
and it is kind of artificial.

755
00:31:19.140 --> 00:31:21.120
The short PR interval is created

756
00:31:21.120 --> 00:31:25.290
because the beginning of the QRS complex widens.

757
00:31:25.290 --> 00:31:27.420
And the delta part is, in essence,

758
00:31:27.420 --> 00:31:30.090
describing that the first part of the QRS complex looks

759
00:31:30.090 --> 00:31:32.610
like a little triangle or a delta wave.

760
00:31:32.610 --> 00:31:33.990
So that is the,

761
00:31:33.990 --> 00:31:36.018
in essence, describing conduction down

762
00:31:36.018 --> 00:31:38.130
that accessory pathway.

763
00:31:38.130 --> 00:31:39.810
Once you get through the accessory pathway

764
00:31:39.810 --> 00:31:43.170
and back onto the main highway down the His Purkinje system,

765
00:31:43.170 --> 00:31:46.320
the rest of the QS complex looks normal.

766
00:31:46.320 --> 00:31:51.320
The problem is that a drug that slows conduction

767
00:31:51.330 --> 00:31:54.090
through the AV node and all the ones that were

768
00:31:54.090 --> 00:31:54.960
on the list there other

769
00:31:54.960 --> 00:31:57.810
than procainamide slow AV conduction,

770
00:31:57.810 --> 00:32:01.410
basically shunt conduction down that pathway.

771
00:32:01.410 --> 00:32:02.640
By blocking the AV node,

772
00:32:02.640 --> 00:32:05.670
you now increase conduction down the accessory pathway

773
00:32:05.670 --> 00:32:07.800
and run the risk of making the,

774
00:32:07.800 --> 00:32:09.000
in essence, hard wiring this

775
00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:12.720
and keeping someone in the pre-excitation pathway longer.

776
00:32:12.720 --> 00:32:15.030
So AV nodal blocking agents,

777
00:32:15.030 --> 00:32:17.580
I don't know that I'd remember procainamide

778
00:32:17.580 --> 00:32:20.220
as the prototype drug here as we want to use,

779
00:32:20.220 --> 00:32:23.190
but I would remember that in the case of pre-excitation,

780
00:32:23.190 --> 00:32:25.500
we don't wanna slow AV conduction

781
00:32:25.500 --> 00:32:28.653
'cause it preferentially shunts down the accessory pathway.

782
00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:32.550
So what to do here, if it's SVT,

783
00:32:32.550 --> 00:32:34.509
you can treat like SVT.

784
00:32:34.509 --> 00:32:36.780
AFib or flutter, again, procainamide

785
00:32:36.780 --> 00:32:38.880
or a drug that doesn't slow AV conduction.

786
00:32:38.880 --> 00:32:41.640
Again, this is almost always in conjunction with your,

787
00:32:41.640 --> 00:32:43.470
one of your cardiology colleagues.

788
00:32:43.470 --> 00:32:48.120
But again, avoid agents that slow AV conduction.

789
00:32:48.120 --> 00:32:50.250
Many of these end up going to electrophysiology

790
00:32:50.250 --> 00:32:52.150
for ablation of the accessory pathway.

791
00:32:54.330 --> 00:32:56.970
Sinus node disease or sick sinus syndrome,

792
00:32:56.970 --> 00:32:59.100
can see all sorts of things with that.

793
00:32:59.100 --> 00:33:01.590
Either slow rates, fast rates.

794
00:33:01.590 --> 00:33:04.800
Key thing here is that when you're looking at this

795
00:33:04.800 --> 00:33:06.390
and you say, "Oh, there's a little hole here,

796
00:33:06.390 --> 00:33:07.740
there's a gap."

797
00:33:07.740 --> 00:33:09.090
What happened during that gap?

798
00:33:09.090 --> 00:33:10.380
Is it a second degree block

799
00:33:10.380 --> 00:33:12.240
and there's a P wave that didn't conduct?

800
00:33:12.240 --> 00:33:13.410
In this case, nothing happened.

801
00:33:13.410 --> 00:33:16.440
The SA node just kind of took a little rest.

802
00:33:16.440 --> 00:33:18.840
Just like with third degree AV block,

803
00:33:18.840 --> 00:33:20.160
for sinus node disease,

804
00:33:20.160 --> 00:33:23.880
you need to be able to correlate EKG abnormalities

805
00:33:23.880 --> 00:33:26.913
with symptoms before that patient ends up with a pacemaker.

806
00:33:29.070 --> 00:33:31.680
V-tach, three or more beats in a row.

807
00:33:31.680 --> 00:33:34.200
So technically a triplet that is a rate

808
00:33:34.200 --> 00:33:37.890
of greater than 100 is non-sustained V-tach.

809
00:33:37.890 --> 00:33:39.300
The sustained versus non-sustained

810
00:33:39.300 --> 00:33:40.890
is strictly a time definition.

811
00:33:40.890 --> 00:33:42.600
Once you hit the 30 second mark,

812
00:33:42.600 --> 00:33:43.950
it becomes sustained V-tach,

813
00:33:43.950 --> 00:33:46.623
under 30 seconds is non-sustained.

814
00:33:48.480 --> 00:33:51.900
Torsades is just a fascinating thing

815
00:33:51.900 --> 00:33:54.420
because it is basically a V-tach

816
00:33:54.420 --> 00:33:56.400
that does not come from a single focus.

817
00:33:56.400 --> 00:33:58.440
It comes from multiple areas around the heart.

818
00:33:58.440 --> 00:34:01.890
So you get this almost sinusoidal-looking pattern

819
00:34:01.890 --> 00:34:04.350
to the ventricular fibulator waves,

820
00:34:04.350 --> 00:34:06.273
typically is drug-associated.

821
00:34:07.710 --> 00:34:10.980
A lot of times goes along with long QT syndrome.

822
00:34:10.980 --> 00:34:12.990
Remember that the QT is the absolute value.

823
00:34:12.990 --> 00:34:15.303
QTC is corrected for heart rate.

824
00:34:17.430 --> 00:34:19.110
The list here, please don't memorize the list,

825
00:34:19.110 --> 00:34:21.810
but recognize that there are classes of drugs

826
00:34:21.810 --> 00:34:24.030
that typically prolong QT interval.

827
00:34:24.030 --> 00:34:27.210
A lot of antibiotics, a lot of the azole antifungals,

828
00:34:27.210 --> 00:34:30.240
psychotropic drugs, and antiarrhythmics are on the list.

829
00:34:30.240 --> 00:34:31.234
And with that, thank you for your time.

830
00:34:31.234 --> 00:34:33.150
(audience applauding)

831
00:34:33.150 --> 00:34:35.450
<v Host>Thank you very much, Dr. Firnhaber.</v>

832
00:34:36.472 --> 00:34:39.055
(bright music)

